From 57d043f265b9d848d02c3541f74f5d055060b4cc Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Volker Badziong <development@richtfest.tech>
Date: Mon, 20 Jul 2026 10:04:51 +0000
Subject: [PATCH 6/7] Stage per-server slice properties across server startup

A game server's load-time peak routinely dwarfs its steady working set --
world generation and asset streaming reach for everything at once -- so a
memory.high sized for the steady state throttles precisely the phase that can
least afford it.

That would merely be slow if the two knobs were independent, but they are
not: memory.high reclaim is the one path that ignores memory.min, because
protection only fends off reclaim driven from OUTSIDE the cgroup. A ceiling
below the load-time peak therefore evicts the server through its own floor,
and the damage is permanent -- nothing faults those pages back except the
workload itself, one at a time. Operators are left with a server pinned well
under a floor that is configured, applied and completely effective.

Add a startup band: WINGS_CG_STARTUP_MEMORY_MIN/_LOW/_HIGH/_MAX and
docker.per_server_slices.startup_defaults, applied when the slice is ensured
before container creation and replaced by the steady band once the server is
up. Only the memory band is staged; cpu/io weights are work-conserving and
cannot evict anything.

The transition reuses detection Wings already performs. The egg's startup
"done" matcher flips the environment to the running state, which reaches
OnStateChange -- so the trigger is per-egg configuration every game already
carries, and no new console parsing is introduced. A startup_grace timer
(default 15m) bounds the startup band, because a ready line that never matches
-- a broken egg, a game that changed its log format -- must not leave a server
on startup properties forever.

Every application now logs the slice it targets, the phase, what triggered it
and the properties applied, with sizes rendered in the units they were
configured with rather than raw byte counts.

Nodes that configure no startup band are unaffected: both phases resolve to
the same properties, which a test asserts.

Co-Authored-By: Claude Opus 4.8 (1M context) <noreply@anthropic.com>
